NAME
    diff - compare files line by line

SYNOPSIS
    diff [OPTION]... FILE1 FILE2
    diff [OPTION]... --from-file=FILE1 FILES...
    diff [OPTION]... --to-file=FILE2 FILES...

DESCRIPTION
    diff compares FILE1 and FILE2 line by line and reports differences.
    Output describes changes needed to turn FILE1 into FILE2.

    When FILE is '-', read standard input. If FILE1 is a directory and
    FILE2 is a file (or vice versa), diff compares the file in the
    directory with the given filename to FILE2.

OPTIONS
    -u N, --unified[=N]
        Output N (default 3) lines of unified context. The most common
        format for patches.

    -c N, --context[=N]
        Output N (default 3) lines of copied context.

    -e, --ed
        Output an ed script.

    -n, --rcs
        Output an RCS format diff.

    -q, --brief
        Report only whether files differ.

    -s, --report-identical-files
        Report when two files are the same.

    -i, --ignore-case
        Ignore case differences in file contents.

    -w, --ignore-all-space
        Ignore all white space.

    -b, --ignore-space-change
        Ignore changes in the amount of white space.

    -B, --ignore-blank-lines
        Ignore changes where all lines are blank.

    --strip-trailing-cr
        Strip trailing carriage return on input.

    -r, --recursive
        Recursively compare any subdirectories found.

    -N, --new-file
        Treat absent files as empty.

    -a, --text
        Treat all files as text.

    --label LABEL
        Use LABEL instead of the file name and time in headers.

    -D NAME, --ifdef=NAME
        Output a merged file with '#ifdef NAME' guards.

    --version
        Output version information and exit.

    --help
        Display help and exit.

OUTPUT FORMAT (unified)
    Lines beginning with '---' and '+++' are the file headers.
    Hunk headers start with '@@'. Lines prefixed with '-' appear only
    in FILE1; lines prefixed with '+' appear only in FILE2.

EXAMPLES
    diff old.txt new.txt
        Show differences in default format.

    diff -u old.c new.c
        Unified diff suitable for a patch file.

    diff -r dir1/ dir2/
        Recursively compare two directories.

    diff -q file1 file2
        Report only whether files are identical.

    diff -i text1.txt text2.txt
        Case-insensitive comparison.

EXIT STATUS
    0   Files are identical.
    1   Files differ.
    2   Error occurred.
